<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-01-26T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-01-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="144" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d144">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.51/1258.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador to
                                    France</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-01-26">
                                    <hi rend="italic">January 26, 1913</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>It is claimed by the six banking groups that at the time Russia and Japan
                            were admitted it was agreed that the Chinese loan should be
                            internationalized. I am unofficially informed that the French Minister
                            of Finance objects to internationalization. I understand from the German
                            Ambassador that he is disposed to represent to the Minister for Foreign
                            Affairs the importance of French agreement to internationalization but
                            awaits instructions from his Government before acting. British
                            Ambassador will also act if instructed. Does the Department desire me to
                            make representations in support of either or both?</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Herrick</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>